'''Hansda Sowvendra Shekhar''' (born 1983) is an Indian writer. 

==ᱡᱤᱭᱚᱱ==
Ethnically, Shekhar is a [[Santal people|Santhal]], one of India's [[Adivasi]] groups; this background is reflected in his fiction.<ref>Ziya Us Salam, '[http://www.frontline.in/the-nation/a-santhal-suppressed/article9873860.ece A Santhal Suppressed]', ''Frontline'' (13 October 2017).</ref> His stories are rich in "fine details that add to the deep dimensions" and "open to us a world we have deliberately dismissed" <ref>{{cite web |url=https://scroll.in/article/772558/the-tribal-world-strikes-back-at-indian-writing-in-english-through-a-doctor |title=The tribal world strikes back at Indian writing in English through a doctor |work=Scroll |author=Binoo K. John |date=November 30, 2015 |accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref> and contain "a surplus of understanding that comes from a kind insider-outsider."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/tlsafHsKkGsFvOzNRp6eGM/Faith-in-the-local.html |title=Faith in the local |work=Livemint |author=Sumana Roy |date=October 17, 2015 |accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref> Indeed, he characterised his first novel as "the first full-fledged Santhal novel written in English, and published by a mainstream publisher."<ref>Sujit Prasad, '[https://antiserious.com/i-am-a-santhal-and-my-opinion-too-should-matter-hansda-sowvendra-shekhar-8b8d226e7153 “I Am a Santhal, and My Opinion Too Should Matter,” says Hansda Sowvendra Shekhar]', ''antiserious.com'' (16 August 2017) [repr. from the ''Boston Coffee House Magazine'' 2014].</ref> Born in [[Ranchi]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/books-and-more-hansda-sowvendra-shekhar-is-a-dedicated-doctor-and-writer-2053574 |title=Hansda Sowvendra Shekhar is a dedicated doctor and writer |work=DNA |author=Kaartikeya Bajpai |date=January 18, 2015 |accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref> Shekhar grew up in [[Ghatshila]] and [[Chakulia]] and went to school in [[Musabani]].<ref>Hansda Sowvendra Shekhar, '[https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/blink/read/not-just-one/article7460270.ece Not just one]', ''The Hindu Business Line'' (24 July 2015)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/aZ43AhlrXibH0u9vem9p5K/Ghatsila-A-nostalgists-map.html |title=Ghatsila: A nostalgist's map |work=Mint Lounge/Livemint |author=Hansda Sowvendra Shekhar |date=April 23, 2016 |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://indianquarterly.com/black/ |title=Black |work=The Indian Quarterly |author=Hansda Sowvendra Shekhar |date=April–June 2018 |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> His parents used to work with [[Hindustan Copper]] in [[Ghatshila]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/express-sunday-eye/playing-with-fire-5334097/ |title=Playing with Fire: Hansda Sowvendra Shekhar on his first children's book |work=The Indian Express |author=Paromita Chakrabarti |date=September 2, 2018 |accessdate=September 2, 2018}}</ref> By profession, he is a medical doctor and is employed as a medical officer with the government of [[Jharkhand]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://scroll.in/article/772558/the-tribal-world-strikes-back-at-indian-writing-in-english-through-a-doctor |title=The tribal world strikes back at Indian writing in English through a doctor |work=Scroll |author=Binoo K. John |date=November 30, 2015 |accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>Sudipta Datta, '[http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/hansda-sowvendra-shekharfighting-a-ban/article19525262.ece Who is Hansda Sowvendra Shekhar, fighting a ban]', ''The Hindu'' (19 August 2017).</ref> based in 2017 in [[Pakur]].<ref>Ziya Us Salam, '[http://www.frontline.in/the-nation/a-santhal-suppressed/article9873860.ece A Santhal Suppressed]', ''Frontline'' (13 October 2017).</ref>

Though Shekhar writes primarily in English, he also translates from Santhali to English <ref>{{cite web |url=https://scroll.in/article/838374/eight-melancholic-introspective-poems-by-parimal-hansda-on-being-a-santhal-today |title=Eight melancholic, introspective poems by Parimal Hansda on being a Santhal today |work=Scroll |author=Parimal Hansda |date=August 20, 2017 |accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asymptotejournal.com/nonfiction/shibu-tudu-memories-of-the-kirta-dangra/ |title=Memories of the Kirta Dangra |work=Asymptote |author=Shibu Tudu |accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asymptotejournal.com/nonfiction/shibu-tudu-memories-of-the-kirta-dangra/santhali/ |title=Memories of the Kirta Dangra (Santhali) |work=Asymptote |author=Shibu Tudu |accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref> and Hindi to English.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thehindu.com/books/i-am-from-the-earth/article19690085.ece |title=I am from the Earth |work=The Hindu |author=Manish Mundra |date=September 16, 2017 |accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usawa.in/in-translation/baba-crows-and-black-smoke.html |title=Baba, Crows and Black Smoke |work=Usawa literary Review |author=Ranendra |date=August 2, 2018 |accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref> 

